<DOC><DOCNO> SJMN91-06331051 </DOCNO><ACCESS> 06331051 </ACCESS><LEADPARA>  Travelers Corp. announced it has agreed to sell the investment bank Dillon,Read andamp; Co. Inc. to the company's management and Barings PLC, a Britishinvestment bank.;   Dillon, Read management and directors would acquire 60percent of the common stock of Dillon, Read Holding Inc., a vehicle created tobuy the investment firm, for an undisclosed price.  </LEADPARA><SECTION>  Business  </SECTION><HEADLINE>  TRAVELERS CORP. WILL SELL BANK TO MANAGEMENT  </HEADLINE><TEXT>     Barings said in London it has agreed to pay $26 million for a 40 percentstake. In addition, Barings said it would buy $52 million in preferred stockin Dillon, Read Holding. The purchase would be financed through the sale ofnew Barings preference shares, Barings said.;   Total proceeds to Travelers,the Hartford-based insurance giant, will be $122 million. Travelers bought thecompany in 1986 for $157.6 million.;   The sale is subject to regulatoryapproval.;   &quot;Travelers has benefited in many ways from our relationship withDillon, Read,&quot; said Travelers Chairman and Chief Executive Officer EdwardBudd.;   &quot;Dillon, Read's operating results have met our expectations over thefive years we have owned it, and we have received net distributions of closeto $30 million,&quot; he said.;   &quot;However, this sale is appropriate and consistentwith our strategy to focus on our core insurance, managed care and investmentbusinesses,&quot; Budd said.;   Barings said it expects the purchase to becompleted by Dec. 15.;   &quot;The proposed transaction will create an importantpartnership between Barings and Dillon, Read,&quot; Barings said. &quot;The two firmsare compatible in activity and philosophy, placing a like value onindependence and integrity.&quot;;   Barings added that the firms were&quot;geographically complementary,&quot; with the 161-year-old Dillon, Read strong inU.S. corporate finance and capital markets, while Barings has similarstrengths in Europe and Asia.;   Budd said he expects Travelers to continueits business relationship with Dillon, Read.;   The 219-year-old Barings, theoldest British merchant bank, said Barings Chairman Peter Baring and DeputyChairman Andrew Tuckey were expected to join the board of Dillon, Read Holdingfollowing the purchase.;   John Birkelund, chairman of Dillon, Read, wouldjoin Barings' board.;   &quot;We hope our valued partnership with The Travelerswill continue to be reflected in a close relationship on projects of mutualinterest,&quot; Birkelund said in a statement. &quot;Dillon, Read and Barings havecomplimentary businesses and consistent strategies and philosophies that wefeel will improve each firm's competitive position.&quot;  </TEXT><BYLINE>  Associated Press  </BYLINE><COUNTRY>  USA  </COUNTRY><CITY>  Hartford, Conn.  </CITY><EDITION>  Stock Final  </EDITION><CODE>  SJ  </CODE><NAME>  San Jose Mercury News  </NAME><PUBDATE>   911126  </PUBDATE> <DAY>  Tuesday  </DAY><MONTH>  November  </MONTH><PG.COL>  14C  </PG.COL><PUBYEAR>  1991  </PUBYEAR><REGION>  WEST  </REGION><STATE>  CA  </STATE><WORD.CT>  386  </WORD.CT><DATELINE>  Tuesday, November 26, 199100331051,SJ1  </DATELINE><COPYRGHT>  Copyright 1991, San Jose Mercury News  </COPYRGHT><LIMLEN>  1  </LIMLEN><LANGUAGE>  ENG  </LANGUAGE></DOC>